  "datePublished": "2026-03-06",
  "description": "Cognitive poetics is the study of how literary forms engage cognitive processes — how the structures of narrative, poetry, and other literary artifacts interact with the reader\u0026rsquo;s (or writer\u0026rsquo;s) mechanisms of perception, memory, categorization, and meaning-making.\nThe field draws on cognitive science and linguistics to analyze literary effects that traditional criticism treats as intuitive or aesthetic. Mark Turner\u0026rsquo;s The Literary Mind (1996) argues that narrative and metaphor are not literary embellishments but fundamental cognitive operations: the mind organizes experience through stories and conceptual blends before it produces anything recognizable as \u0026ldquo;literature.\u0026rdquo; Jerome Bruner\u0026rsquo;s Acts of Meaning (1990) makes the complementary argument that narrative is a primary mode of thought — people understand their lives by constructing stories about them, and the stories\u0026rsquo; formal properties (sequencing, causation, perspective) shape the understanding they produce [@bruner1990].\n",
